install node_modeles_repo:
    npm install express --save
nodemonlocal:
    npm install nodemon --save-dev
docker build -t name_img .
docker run -d -p 8080:80 name_img
Lists all container:
    docker ps -aq (q for ids)
Remove all containers:
    docker rm $(docker ps -aq)
Stop all running containers:
    docker stop $(docker ps -aq)
Run the Docker Container:
    docker run -d -p 3306:3306 --name mariadb-container name_img
start a bash shell session:
    docker exec -it name_cotainer bash
displays images:
    docker images
display status runing:
    docker logs container
hot reload (No need to rebuild the image):
    docker run -v /Users/amel-has/Desktop/inception/project/srcs/requirements/mariadb:/app -d -p 3306:3306 --name mariadb-container name_img
    docker run -v ($pwd):/app:ro(read only) -d -p 3306:3306 --name mariadb-container name_img
anonymous volume docker:
    docker run -v repownatsave -d -p 3306:3306 --name mariadb-container name_img
bind amount:
    docker run -d -it --name devtest mount type=bind,source="$(pwd)"/target,target=/app nginx:latest

Differences between -v and --mount behavior:
    Because the -v and --volume flags have been a part of Docker for a long time, their behavior cannot be changed. This means that there is one behavior that is different between -v and --mount.
    If you use -v or --volume to bind-mount a file or directory that does not yet exist on the Docker host, -v creates the endpoint for you. It is always created as a directory.
    If you use --mount to bind-mount a file or directory that does not yet exist on the Docker host, Docker does not automatically create it for you, but generates an error.
MariaDB:
    Default Port: 3306
WordPress:
    Default Port: 80 (HTTP) / 443 (HTTPS)
Nginx:
    Default Port: 80 (HTTP) / 443 (HTTPS)
